# Documentation voice and SEO (ECP)

## Voice

- **Technically friendly, light**: precise terms, low-jargon sentences, minimal hype.
- **Forward-moving**: prefer “what this is / why it matters / how to use it next.”
- **Helpful, not spammy**: avoid buzzword piles, “ultimate guide” phrasing, and repetitive keyword loops.
- **Clarity over cleverness**: simple headings, short paragraphs, concrete examples.
- **Active voice + second person**: “you can…” / “run…” / “define…”.
- **No emojis**: avoid emojis in headings, body text, tables, and UI callouts.

## Terminology and naming

- **First mention on a page**: write **“ECP (Execution Control Protocol)”**.
- **After that**: alternate naturally between **ECP**, **Execution Control Protocol**, and **the protocol** when context is clear.
- **Avoid**: repeating “Execution Control Protocol” in every paragraph; it should read like normal technical writing.

## SEO that still reads well

- **Intent-first intro**: first 2–3 sentences should answer what the page is for and who it helps.
- **Headings**: sentence case; use clear, specific H2s that match real queries (no clickbait).
- **Internal links**: add 2–5 relevant links to deeper docs (concepts, security, MCP relationship, spec/CLI) where helpful.
- **Comparisons**: state what ECP is and isn’t; use crisp “X is for…, ECP is for…” framing.

## Content checks before publishing

- Title + description include **ECP** and **Execution Control Protocol** at least once (naturally).
- H1 is unique and matches the title’s intent.
- A “Next steps” or “Related reading” section exists when appropriate.
